## GitLab — what works, what doesn't

### No token in the container (by design)

You hold **no** GitLab token. This is intentional (security architecture §R6). All
GitLab operations run exclusively through the **Warden**, which holds all tokens and
enforces the policy — reachable at each configured git host itself (see below), not at
a separate name.

### Your policy & limits — read `__WARDEN_TOML_PATH__`

Your active rules are not hardcoded — they live in **`__WARDEN_TOML_PATH__`** (mounted
read-only for you; the Warden enforces this same file). **Read it** to learn your real
limits before you push or open MRs:

- **`branch_prefixes`** — the list of prefixes your branches **must** carry (at least one) to
  be pushable (R2) and to be allowed as an MR `source_branch` (R3). For this sandbox it
  currently includes `__BRANCH_PREFIX_EXAMPLE__` (a legacy single-value
  `branch_prefix = "..."` form may also appear). The examples below use
  `__BRANCH_PREFIX_EXAMPLE__`; substitute whatever prefix your `warden.toml` actually specifies
  if it differs.
- **`allowed_projects`** — the only projects you may touch at all (R6); anything else is denied.
- **`max_open_mrs` / `max_open_branches` / `max_writes_per_hour`** — your quotas (R5).

```bash
cat __WARDEN_TOML_PATH__        # your branch_prefixes, allowed_projects and quotas
```

### GitLab runs through the Warden

`git` is automatically redirected — no difference in usage:

```bash
git clone https://gitlab.com/group/project.git   # transparently routed through the Warden
git fetch && git push origin __BRANCH_PREFIX_EXAMPLE__my-branch     # likewise
```

This works identically for every configured git host — `gitlab.com`, a self-hosted
`my-gitlab.de`, whatever `warden.toml` lists — not just the example above.

REST calls (create MR, trigger CI, etc.) go directly against the Warden. The rule is the
same for every configured host: for a git host `X`, the Warden's REST API is at
`__FORGE_REST_BASE__` — substitute the actual hostname of the project's own git remote
for `<host>` (e.g. `gitlab.com`, `my-gitlab.de`); same port, same `/api/v4` suffix,
regardless of which host you're working against:

```bash
# Create MR
curl -sS "__FORGE_REST_BASE__/projects/<id>/merge_requests" \
  -H "Content-Type: application/json" \
  -d '{"source_branch":"__BRANCH_PREFIX_EXAMPLE__my-branch","target_branch":"main","title":"..."}'

# Comment on an MR (top-level note)
curl -sS -X POST "__FORGE_REST_BASE__/projects/<id>/merge_requests/<iid>/notes" \
  -H "Content-Type: application/json" \
  -d '{"body":"looks good"}'

# Inline code-review comment on a specific file/line (a "discussion" with a position).
# Get base_sha/head_sha/start_sha from the MR's diff_refs:
#   GET …/merge_requests/<iid>/changes  →  .diff_refs
curl -sS -X POST "__FORGE_REST_BASE__/projects/<id>/merge_requests/<iid>/discussions" \
  -H "Content-Type: application/json" \
  -d '{"body":"this can overflow",
       "position":{"position_type":"text",
         "base_sha":"<base>","head_sha":"<head>","start_sha":"<start>",
         "new_path":"src/main.rs","new_line":12}}'

# Reply in an existing review thread
curl -sS -X POST "__FORGE_REST_BASE__/projects/<id>/merge_requests/<iid>/discussions/<discussion_id>/notes" \
  -H "Content-Type: application/json" \
  -d '{"body":"fixed in the latest push"}'

# Edit an MR (title / description / labels) or close it (state_event=close)
curl -sS -X PUT "__FORGE_REST_BASE__/projects/<id>/merge_requests/<iid>" \
  -H "Content-Type: application/json" \
  -d '{"title":"Refactor X","description":"...","state_event":"close"}'

# Trigger CI pipeline
curl -sS -X POST "__FORGE_REST_BASE__/projects/<id>/pipeline" \
  -H "Content-Type: application/json" \
  -d '{"ref":"__BRANCH_PREFIX_EXAMPLE__my-branch"}'

# Merge — NOT allowed: the Warden answers 403 (R4) and sends no token upstream.
#   PUT …/merge_requests/<iid>/merge        (also state_event=merge on the edit above)
```

These are **every** write endpoint the Warden permits — anything else (e.g. creating
branches/tags directly, editing project settings) is default-denied. You may create MRs
and trigger CI only for `__BRANCH_PREFIX_EXAMPLE__*` branches (R2/R3), and comment/discuss/edit only on MRs
**you** authored (R3); merging is never allowed (R4). The Warden expects **no auth** from
the agent — token injection happens internally.

**Responses come back as plain, uncompressed JSON.** The Warden decompresses any
upstream `Content-Encoding` (gzip/deflate) before relaying and strips the header, so
the body always matches the headers — no `--compressed`, no `gunzip`, no
`Accept-Encoding` juggling needed. Just read the body:

```bash
curl -sS "__FORGE_REST_BASE__/groups/<id>/projects"
```

### Warden not active (stage 01 / no Warden profile)

No token, no Warden → **no write access to GitLab**. Public repos are readable
via the forward proxy (`git clone` / `git fetch`). Push will fail.

### Hard limits (Warden enforces, cannot be bypassed)

| Allowed                                      | Forbidden                                                          |
| ---------------------------------------------- | -------------------------------------------------------------------- |
| Push to `__BRANCH_PREFIX_EXAMPLE__*` branches  | Push to `main`, `develop`, or branches without an allowed prefix     |
| Create MRs, comment, trigger CI                | Merge MRs (→ 403, always)                                          |
| Read (API GETs, git fetch/clone)               | Read tokens from the environment (none present)                    |
| Up to 5 open MRs at a time                     | More than 60 write actions/hour                                    |

